{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514726"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12368"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12368","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12368"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.37,0.17,0.1,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77810"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12368"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63331"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1095"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"1308"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"1829"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39049"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77810","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77810"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 38-year-old woman presents with one-week history of pain and redness in her left eye. The pain is severe and is associated with photophobia and lacrimation. Her medical history includes inflammatory bowel disease, and she is a smoker. On examination there is no discharge around the eye. The pupil is constricted and sluggish in reaction to light. The eyeball is tender to touch. With magnification (slit lamp), inflammatory cells can seen deposited in the corneal endothelium and her visual acuity is reduced. The intraocular pressure is 21 mm Hg (10-21 mm Hg).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Scleritis","Iridocyclitis","Keratitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Conjunctivitis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe symptoms of this patient accompanied with constricted and sluggish pupil directs the diagnosis towards \u003Cstrong\u003Eiridocyclitis. \u003C/strong\u003EKeratic precipitates (inflammatory cells) deposited in the corneal epithelium are pathognomonic of iridocyclitis. The raised intraocular pressure (IOP) could be a salient feature of acute angle closure glaucoma, but iridocyclitis may also present with mildly raised pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma \u003C/strong\u003Eis an ocular emergency which presents with severe pain, redness and watering in the affected eye, halos around light, reduced vision, nausea and vomiting. The pupil is dilated in such circumstances, but in this case the patient presents with a constricted pupil. Acute angle closure glaucoma results from a rapid increase in intraocular pressure due to closure of anterior angle of eye causing outflow obstruction of aqueous humour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis \u003C/strong\u003Eis the inflammation or infection of the transparent membrane (conjunctiva) that lines the eyelid and covers the white part of eyeball. It presents with redness, itching, a gritty feeling, discharge that forms a crust during the night that may cause difficulty in eye opening in the morning, lacrimation. The pupil and IOP remains normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeratitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition in which the cornea becomes inflamed. It also causes redness and pain in the eye with a foreign body sensation, lacrimation, photophobia, blurred vision and discharge but usually does not affect the pupil or the IOP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScleritis \u003C/strong\u003Eis the inflammation of white part of the eye (sclera) usually caused by an autoimmune disorder such as rheumatoid arthritis, lupus, Sjogren\u2019s syndrome, scleroderma, gout, atopy, and granulomatosis with polyangiitis. Symptoms of scleritis can include pain that radiates to the forehead, brow, jaw, or sinuses, tearing or photophobia, ocular tenderness, and decreased visual acuity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Iridocyclitis is uveitis confined to the iris and ciliary body and may have an infective, traumatic or autoimmune origin.","Inflammatory bowel disease is associated with an increased risk of developing iridocyclitis."],"references":["Harman LE, Margo CE, Roetzheim RG. Uveitis: the collaborative diagnostic evaluation. Am Fam Physician. 2014 Nov 15;90(10):711-6. PMID: 25403035. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25403035/","Agrawal RV, Murthy S, Sangwan V, Biswas J. Current approach in diagnosis and management of anterior uveitis. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2010 Jan-Feb;58(1):11-9. doi: 10.4103/0301-4738.58468. PMID: 20029142; PMCID: PMC2841369.","Duplechain A, Conrady CD, Patel BC, Baker S. Uveitis. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31082037. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31082037/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63331"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12368"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63331"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T12:29:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T12:30:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77810"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1095","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1095"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammatory bowel disease","synonyms":["IBD"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-06T23:28:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-20T20:46:57+09:30"},"relati